# Coding Standards

These standards are mandatory for anyone working on this repository.

## 1) Scope and Simplicity
- Keep this project as a simple demo chatbot application.
- Prefer clean, small, readable code over advanced patterns.
- Do not add unnecessary abstractions, frameworks, or complexity.
- No authentication unless explicitly requested.

## 2) Required Project Structure
- Keep frontend and backend in separate top-level directories:
  - `backend/`
  - `frontend/`

## 3) Backend Standards
- Stack:
  - Python
  - `uv` for project/dependency management
  - FastAPI
  - PostgreSQL
  - Alembic for migrations
  - OpenAI for LLM responses
- Required backend file layout:
  - `backend/main.py` (entry point)
  - `backend/app.py` (FastAPI app)
  - `backend/router.py` (single router file for endpoints)
  - `backend/config.py` (configuration via Pydantic settings)
- Keep backend modules minimal and purposeful.

## 4) Database Standards
- Persist all chat data in PostgreSQL.
- Conversations and messages must be stored in database tables.
- Support multi-turn conversation flows with stored history.
- Maintain a short context window when building LLM input.

## 5) API Feature Requirements
- Must support:
  - Create conversation
  - List conversations
  - Send messages
  - Multi-turn message flow
- Keep API design straightforward and demo-friendly.

## 6) Frontend Standards
- Stack:
  - React
  - Vite
  - Tailwind CSS
- Provide a minimal UI for:
  - Viewing conversations
  - Creating a conversation
  - Sending and viewing messages

## 7) Documentation and Tests Policy
- Do not add extra documentation files unless explicitly requested.
- Do not add test cases unless explicitly requested.
- Focus on working code first.

## 8) Configuration Rules
- Use `backend/config.py` for config management with Pydantic.
- Keep only intentionally approved defaults.
- Environment-driven values should be validated on startup.

## 9) Change Discipline
- Follow existing naming and structure conventions.
- Keep diffs focused and small.
- Do not introduce unrelated refactors while implementing features.
